  "diary": "Woke up to grey skies and that familiar Seattle drizzle. The SR-520 closure had everyone talking on the bus this morning—I was grateful I'd already planned the U-District route. The shop was steady all day, the kind of rainy Tuesday where people cluster around tables nursing their drinks longer than usual. I spent a good chunk of the morning walking Maya through our pour-over technique; she's getting there, just needs more confidence. Grabbed soup at the counter during lunch and just... watched the rain streak the windows. By afternoon, the crowd had thinned out, which gave me time to reorganize the back. Stopped at Safeway on the way home and the produce looked decent for once. Up on the rooftop, my basil's really thriving—pruned some for tonight's pasta. The kombucha's right on schedule too. Made dinner with everything fresh, which felt good. Spent the evening bottling the second batch and journaling my notes on the mango-ginger blend. There's something settling about a day like this—contained, purposeful, quiet.",
  "thought_process": "Today felt like a day where I needed routine to ground me. The rain and the bridge closure meant the city was a bit chaotic, but I leaned into what I could control—showing up early, training Maya carefully, staying present with customers. I think I've been craving more hands-on work lately, less screen time, more actual making and growing. That's why the rooftop and the kombucha session felt so restorative tonight. Work was solid but not draining, which meant I had energy for my projects. The fresh produce stop was deliberate—I'm trying to eat more intentionally, use what I grow. By the time I was journaling flavor notes at 10pm, I realized I'd been in a good headspace most of the day, unhurried. The drizzle helped. Everything moved slower.",
